  <h2>When to use a link skip</h2>
  <p>All nhs.uk pages must include a link skip in the header, following <a href="https://design-system.service.gov.uk/components/skip-link/">guidance in the GOV.UK Design System</a>.</p>

  <h2 id="how-it-works">How link skips work</h2>
  <p>Some people use the tab key on their keyboard to navigate through the links and form elements on a web page. Including a link skip gives users the option to bypass the top-level navigation links and jump to the main content on the page.</p>
  <p>The link skip component is visually hidden until a keyboard press activates it.</p>

  <h2>How to use a link skip</h2>
  <p>Place the link skip near the top of the page so it becomes available as one of the first keyboard interactions.</p>
  <p>The destination should point to the main content area of the page. If the target is not normally focusable, make sure your page implementation still moves keyboard focus to a useful location.</p>
  <p>Keep the text short and obvious. In most cases, "Skip to main content" is the clearest option.</p>

  <h3>Accessibility</h3>
  <p>The link skip is only helpful if it works with a real target on the page. Always check that the destination exists and that keyboard users can continue from the skipped-to content without getting lost.</p>

  <h2>Research</h2>
  <p>If you have used link skips, please share your user research findings.</p>

